{
  "doc_id": "52533",
  "text": "A number of intrusion detection systems used sequences of system calls to train a Hidden Markov Model (HMM) classifier [CITATION_1] [18] [CITATION_2] [4] [CITATION_3] . However, each system differs in the technique used for raising anomaly signal. Wang et al. [CITATION_4] , for example, raise anomaly signal when the probability of the whole sequence is below certain threshold. Warrender et al. [CITATION_5] , on the other hand, declares a sequence as anomalous when the probability of one system call within a sequence is below the threshold. Cho and Park [CITATION_6] used HMM for modeling normal root privilege operations only. Hoang et al. [CITATION_7] introduced a multi-layer detection technique that combines both outcomes from applying the Sliding Window approach and the HMM approach.",
